01:46:22.000 --> 01:46:34.000
The second office I ran was also for education at the community college level because the majority of underserved their first after graduate of high school.

01:46:34.000 --> 01:46:43.000
Their next step is the community college, not a four year university. Because they can't afford it or they're not.

01:46:43.000 --> 01:46:58.000
The community colleges are closer to them and more affordable. So I ran for the one, the southern most community college district that's adjacent to Tijuana. It's called Southwestern Community College.

01:46:58.000 --> 01:47:12.000
I ran for that office. And before I decided to run, I pulled together Latino leaders throughout the area.

01:47:12.000 --> 01:47:22.000
And they unanimously said they would support me. So I decided that I'd run because I had a base. They would support me.

01:47:22.000 --> 01:47:33.000
And the majority of the ethnic groups were in Spanish, obviously in the South Bay, next to Tijuana.

01:47:33.000 --> 01:47:54.000
Unfortunately, one of the professors got into some hot water in the district and he convinced his brother to run so that he would have a relative to defend him when he got because he was getting into trouble.

01:47:54.000 --> 01:48:09.000
And this was after the promise of all the leaders that they were supporting. Well, the end result was that we had two Hispanics running in an angle, very wealthy from Coronado.

01:48:09.000 --> 01:48:21.000
The district also, that's called Gerrymandering, included the wealthy, Anglos from Coronado, one of the wealthiest community in San Diego. That was part of the district.

01:48:21.000 --> 01:48:39.000
And I was outspent again. And she was elected official from Coronado. So it was a close phrase. And the most voters voted for Hispanic, but there were two Hispanics.

01:48:39.000 --> 01:48:59.000
And so I came in second. That was my second experience. That in the last time I ran was for City Council. I've been involved in redistricting. It's done every 10 years after the census count.

01:48:59.000 --> 01:49:18.000
The enumeration changes districts because they come unbalanced through 10 years of growth. Their growth is not even. It's very uneven. And so you have to redraw lines to comply with the US Constitution of one person, one vote.

01:49:18.000 --> 01:49:32.000
Really one person, not one man, but one person one vote. And you redistribute the so you draw lines. And I've been involved since 1980 in redistricting.

01:49:32.000 --> 01:49:51.000
My first effort was redrawing the lines for the Stereo-California. For Stereo-Sembley and St. Ten years later, I was asked by the county chief administrator of officer to help him redraw the county lines.

01:49:51.000 --> 01:50:05.000
So I served on the county redistricting. The next time there was a change of method of how people got selected to be and to make it less partisan or political.

01:50:05.000 --> 01:50:27.000
So I asked the St. San Diego chose to have judges select commissioners to draw the lines. I was honored to be selected by judges to be redistricting the city of San Diego lines.

01:50:27.000 --> 01:50:56.000
The most recent was the 2010 census and the city again had to redraw lines. The citizens of the Latino residents, San Diego, were being left out. And they created a Latino redistricting committee to shadow the work done by people appointed by the government.

01:50:56.000 --> 01:51:11.000
And I was selected the chairman of the Latino redistricting committee. So we influenced the drawing and created for the first time a district that was majority Latino.

01:51:12.000 --> 01:51:25.000
Latino residents, not voters, but it was Latino. And they've asked me to run. So I ran for the last time for city council.

01:51:26.000 --> 01:51:40.000
I was also of the newly created 9th district. It was a new district because of the population growth in San Diego. And it was a Latino majority district, the 9th district tonight.

01:51:40.000 --> 01:51:54.000
And the voter turnout was less than 10%. Those who could vote less than 10% turned out to vote.

01:51:54.000 --> 01:52:10.000
And the voter turnout was less than 10% turned out to be the same. And the voter turnout was less than 10% turned out to be the same.

